<?xml version="1.0" standalone='no'?><!--*-nxml-*-->
<!DOCTYPE service-group SYSTEM "avahi-service.dtd">
<!--
  discodb2 — Avahi (mDNS / DNS-SD) service advertisement.

  Installed to /etc/avahi/services/discodb2.service by scripts/avahi-setup.sh
  and published by the SYSTEM avahi-daemon. This is the OS mDNS responder —
  the backend process is NOT involved and there is ZERO cost on the backend's
  hot path. avahi-daemon is event-driven: it answers the rare multicast query
  and otherwise sits idle (no polling, no per-frame work). Safe on a Pi 1B+.

  What it does:
    * Advertises the backend WebSocket/HTTP endpoint as a DNS-SD service of
      type _http._tcp on BACKEND_PORT (8765, DESIGN §3.1) so DNS-SD browsers
      (e.g. macOS "Bonjour", `avahi-browse -a`, `dns-sd -B _http._tcp`) can
      DISCOVER the box by service rather than by IP.
    * Relies on avahi-daemon ALSO publishing the host A-record as
      <host-name>.local. avahi-setup.sh pins host-name=discodb, so the Pi is
      reachable at  http://discodb.local:8765  and  ws://discodb.local:8765/ws
      with no IP typing.

  NOTE the browser caveat: JavaScript in a page CANNOT enumerate DNS-SD/mDNS
  (there is no browser API for it), so this <service> record is for OS-level
  discovery tooling, not for the web app to "find" the Pi. The web app does not
  need to: it is SERVED from the Pi, and both frontends default their WebSocket
  to ws://<location.hostname>:8765/ws — i.e. the SAME host that served the page
  (see frontend/cockpit src/state/store.ts and frontend/copilot src/lib/
  store.svelte.ts). So a human types the friendly name once (http://discodb.local)
  and the WS auto-targets discodb.local too. Friendly host A-record + same-host
  WS default = no IP typing anywhere.

  EDIT host/port via /etc/discodb2/discodb2.env and re-run avahi-setup.sh; this
  file is a template materialised from BACKEND_PORT at provisioning time.
-->
<service-group>
  <!-- Service instance name shown in DNS-SD browsers. %h expands to the
       Avahi host-name (discodb), so browsers show "discodb2 on discodb". -->
  <name replace-wildcards="yes">discodb2 on %h</name>

  <service>
    <type>_http._tcp</type>
    <!-- Backend WebSocket/HTTP port — DESIGN §3.1 default. Kept in sync with
         BACKEND_PORT by avahi-setup.sh. -->
    <port>8765</port>
    <!-- Hint for DNS-SD clients that probe the WS endpoint directly. The web
         app does NOT read these (it can't enumerate mDNS); purely advisory. -->
    <txt-record>path=/ws</txt-record>
    <txt-record>app=discodb2</txt-record>
  </service>
</service-group>
